post_text: The Florence Five Board of Trustees is pleased to announce that Jamie Horton will be the new assistant principal at Johnsonville High School for the 2020-21 school year. Ms. Horton is coming to us from Fort Dorchester High School in North Charleston where she served as Assistant Principal. She has also served as the Hartsville Athletic Director and taught South Carolina Social Studies at Darlington Middle School. Ms. Horton received her undergraduate degrees from Coker College and the University of South Carolina. She received her Masters of Education in Educational Leadership from Arkansas State University. Ms. Horton looks forward to beginning her career as a Flash and continuing the success of Johnsonville High School‚Äôs pattern of all-around excellence.

Florence School District Five will be closed through April 30, 2020.

Parents are asked to return student work packets that were given out previously on April 1-3, 2020 from 9:00am to 7:00pm . Drop off containers will be located at the front entrance of each school building. New student work packets will be mailed to you on April 2, 2020.

If your mailing address has changed and needs to be updated, please contact your child's school immediately so that it can be updated prior to April 2 when packets are mailed.

All offices will remain open for phone calls from 9:00am to 3:00pm Monday through Friday. Student meals will continue to be provided at locations throughout the district.

Any further updates will be provided via the district's Bright Arrow system, our website, and social media. Thank you for your attention and cooperation!

post_text:
Congratulations to Mrs. Tiffany Pigate for being named the Florence County School District Five Teacher of the Year for 2019-20 school year.

Mrs. Pigate is a 4th grade teacher at Johnsonville Elementary School. She has 13 years teaching experience with the last 5 years teaching in Florence District Five.

Mrs. Pigate graduated from Johnsonville High School in 2003. She attended Coastal Carolina University and finished with a BA in elementary education. Mrs. Pigate is passionate about reading and hopes to instill a love of books in as many children as possible.

She has been married to Derek Pigate for 10 years, and they are the parents of two little boys, Kellan and Mason.

Mrs. Pigate says, ‚ÄúIt has been a life-long dream to teach at JES, and I am so excited and completely humbled by the opportunity to represent Florence School District Five as Teacher of the Year.‚Äù

Join us in celebrating this great honor with Mrs. Pigate!

post_text:
Rising 7th Graders T-dap Vaccine Information
The South Carolina Department of Health and Environmental Control (DHEC) wants to assure that all children and teens receive recommended vaccines to prevent disease. DHEC reminds parents and guardians that South Carolina law requires that all students entering 7th grade receive one (1) dose of Tdap vaccine. The Tdap vaccine protects preteens and teens from three serious diseases: tetanus, diphtheria, and pertussis (whooping cough).

We are reminding you now so that you have time to plan for your child to be vaccinated early, before the start of 7th grade. Beat the back to school rush, a good time to get all of these vaccines is during a yearly health checkup. Talk to your child‚Äôs health care provider now about what vaccines he or she needs. Ask about these vaccines at a physical exam required for sports, school or camp. Make sure you get an updated SC Certificate of Immunization to give to your school nurse. This certificate is required by state law for school attendance.

post_text: Our district is deeply concerned and saddened by the recent events in Florida. We wish to reassure our parents and students that security is a top priority in Florence Five. We realize that you may be unaware of ongoing security upgrades. Since October, the district has initiated and is currently in the process of enhancing our present security system, which will greatly enhance our safety protocol. The security enhancements have been made possible through grant funds received from the state. Security enhancements include the upgrading of camera systems at all schools to allow local law enforcement immediate access during any school emergency. All front entrances will be equipped with a buzz-in system to restrict entrance into the building, and secondary entrances will be locked and require a pass key to open. Cost of this project will be in excess of $300,000 and will be completed within the next six weeks.

She definitely touched the lives of the employees and students of the Florence District Five Family, and she will be greatly missed.
The funeral service will be on Sunday, December 31, at 2:00 pm at Union Methodist Church, 8206 Rose Hill Road, Georgetown. The visitation will be immediately following.

post_text: Seniors, Jada Parsons and Maggie Leviner, have signed letters of intent to play softball at Florence-Darlington Technical College for the 2018-2019 school year. Jada and Maggie have both been stand-outs on the Johnsonville High School softball team for the past four years. Their signing event was held in the JHS cafeteria on Tuesday, December 12, 2017. Jada and Maggie were congratulated by their parents; softball teammates; Coach, Kaitlin Erikson; and Principal, Sam Tuten. On behalf of Johnsonville High School, Florence School District Five would like to congratulate Jada and Maggie on their accomplishments and wish them the best of luck at Florence-Darlington Technical College next fall!
